\textbf{Question:
Which object is less likely to change shape if you attempted to cut it?}
\textbf{Description:}
In the first clip, a person with long, dark, matte nails is holding a decorative light bulb. \textcolor{ForestGreen}{The light bulb made of glass and metal is illuminated with a purple hue and has a holographic effect inside}, creating a shimmering appearance. The person rotates the light bulb, showcasing its design and the light it emits. In the second clip, a hand is holding a \textcolor{ForestGreen}{red, textured object that resembles a piece of candy} or a similar material. The hand uses a small knife to cut into the object, revealing \textcolor{ForestGreen}{its interior which appears to be a smooth, gel-like substance}.
\textbf{Thinking:} The light bulb in the first clip is a rigid object which would \textcolor{Red}{likely shatter or break if cut}. The candy-like object in the second clip, however, is flexible and \textcolor{Red}{can be cut without changing its overall shape significantly}, as it is designed to be cut and consumed. \textcolor{Red}{Given this analysis, the object that is least likely to change shape if cut is the candy-like object}.
